 their significance to queer and black freedom.Keeling reads selected works, such as Sun Ra’s 1972 film Space is the Place and the 2005 film The Aggressives, to juxtapose the Afrofuturist tradition of speculative imagination with the similar “speculations” of corporate and financial institutions. In connecting a queer, cinematic reordering of time with the new possibilities technology offers, Keeling thinks with and through a vibrant conception of the imagination as a gateway to queer times and black futures, and the previously unimagined spaces that they can conjure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aAfrican American sexual minorities. 0aAfrican Americans in mass media. 0aQueer theory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAfro-Asian.  aAfrofuturism.  aAgamben.  aAlice Coltrane.  aArthur Jafa.  aC. L. R. James.  aÉdouard Glissant.  aGilbert Simondon.  aGilles Deleuze.  aGiorgio Agamben.  aGrace Jones.  aKenya.  aSun Ra.  aarchipelago.  achattel slavery.  acolonization.  acorporate scenarios.  aerrantry.  afantasy fiction.  afinance capital.  afinancialization.  afuturity.  agender.  aimagination.  aincommensuration.  ainterdisciplinarity.  aopacity.  apoetics.  apolicing.  apopular culture.  aqueer temporality.  arace.  aracial capitalism.  ascience fiction.  asexuality.  asocieties of control.  aspeculation.  asurrealism.  atechnē.  atemporality.  athe Americas.  atransgender.  atransindividuation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071028108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072272740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479841998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479841998.jpg  a978-3-11